III.Data Transformation

3.1 Data Acquisitiion

  • Download the weather website by httr and GET function;
  • Extract the table data from the website by html_table function from rvest package.
library(httr)
library(rvest)
from.url<-'https://i-weather.com/weather/washington/history/monthly-history/?gid=4140963&station=19064&month=TODOMONTH&year=TODOYEAR&language=english&country=us-united-states'
todo<-expand.grid(2019:2020,1:12)
names(todo)<-c('year','month')
todo<-todo[order(todo$year,todo$month),]


apply(todo,1,function(xxx)
{
cat(paste(xxx,collapse=","),"====\n")
   gsub('TODOYEAR',xxx[1],from.url)->inter.url
   gsub('TODOMONTH',xxx[2],inter.url)->inter.url
   
   while(1)
   {
   GET(inter.url)->inter.web
   if(length(grep('</html>',content(inter.web,'text')))) break;
   }
   
   read_html(inter.web)->inter.webcontent
   html_table(inter.webcontent)->inter.tables
   sapply(inter.tables,function(ttt) "Daily minimum temperature" %in% names(ttt))->table.wanted
   
   inter.tables[[which(table.wanted)]]->table.wanted
   
   return(table.wanted)
})->resu

We download a complete weather dataset with 10 variables of 24 months from year 2019 to 2020, rbind and save them as a data.frame; the data can be exported as an xlsx file or saved as RData format.

3.2 Data Manipulation

  • Select 6 most relevent variables out of 10 for later analysis
  • Rename variables’ column names concicely. For example, change Daily minimum temperature to min_temp.
  • A few days of weather data from 2019-2020 are missing, for example, there is no data for 2020-12-30; therefore, we fill in the data of those missing days and mark their values as NAs.
  • Save the data in data.table format and order by date.
library(data.table)
library(anytime)

load('dat.RData')
setDT(dat)

dat<-dat[,.(date=anydate(Date),
            min_temp=`Daily minimum temperature`,
            max_temp=`Daily maximum temperature`,
            max_steady_wind=`Maximum steady wind`,
            total_daily_precipitation=`Total daily precipitation`,
            description=Description)]

dat[order(date)]->dat
dat[,min_temp:=as.numeric(gsub('°C','',min_temp))]
dat[,max_temp:=as.numeric(gsub('°C','',max_temp))]
dat[,max_steady_wind:=as.numeric(gsub(' Km/h','',max_steady_wind))]
dat[,total_daily_precipitation:=as.numeric(gsub('mm','',total_daily_precipitation))]
        

dat[,range(date)]
## [1] "2019-01-01" "2020-12-28"
all.days<-seq(anydate("2019-01-01"),anydate('2020-12-31'),by='1 days')
days.miss<-anydate(setdiff(all.days,dat[,date]))  # 5 days missing 

toadd<-data.table(date=anydate(days.miss),min_temp=NA,
                  max_temp=NA,max_steady_wind=NA,total_daily_precipitation=NA,description=NA)

rbind(dat,toadd)->dat

dat[order(date)]->dat
dim(dat)
## [1] 731   6

IV.Missing values

We would like to explore some meaningful patterns based on the distribution of missing values ie.NAs from our weather dataset. (Note: given a fact that our Bike datasets have no missing values, the weather dataset would be our sole data.table to analyze NAs.)

Data table: dat.dt.RData Varibles of our concern: ‘min_temp’, ‘max_temp’, ‘max_steady_wind’, ‘total_daily_precipitation’, ‘description’

library(data.table)
library(ggplot2)
library(anytime)
load('dat.dt.RData')

dat[,year:=year(date)]
dat[,month:=month(date)]
dat[,weekday:=wday(date)]

vars.considered<-c('min_temp','max_temp','max_steady_wind','total_daily_precipitation','description')

# Functions for heatmaps, which take in matrix
makeheatmap1<-function(interMAT)
{
       reshape2:::melt(interMAT)->tu
       tu$Var2<-ordered(tu$Var2,levels=colnames(interMAT))
       tu$Var1<-ordered(tu$Var1,levels=rev(unique(row.names(interMAT))))
       tu$value<-ordered(tu$value,levels=c(0,1),labels=c('No','Yes'))
       ggplot(tu,aes(x=Var2,y=Var1,fill=value)) +
             geom_tile(width=0.9,show.legend=T) +
             scale_x_discrete(expand=expansion(0)) +
             scale_y_discrete(expand=expansion(0)) +
             labs(x='',y='',fill='isNA') +
             theme(axis.text.y=element_blank(),axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90,vjust=0.5,hjust=1),axis.ticks.y=element_blank())+
             scale_fill_manual(values=c('grey','#1569C7'))

}

4.1 Heatmap for overall pattern

Firstly, we would like to present an overall missing-value distribution of continuous days from 2019-01-01 to 2020-12-31 (total 731 days) and the plot shows:

  • X : 6 most relevent variables Y: missing patterns (each day from 2019-01-01 to 2020-12-31)
  • Vertically, variable ‘max_steady_wind’ has most missing values.
  • Horizontally, missing values concentrate at the end of the year 2019 and year 2020
what<-dat[,..vars.considered]
inter.rowname<-as.character(dat[,date])

is.na(what)->to
row.names(to)<-inter.rowname
as.integer(to)->to2
matrix(to2,nrow=nrow(to))->to2
dimnames(to2)<-dimnames(to)

makeheatmap1(to2)

4.2 Visna() for overall pattern

Visna() is another method to explore the potential patterns of missing-value distribution of continuous days (731 days)

  • X : 6 most relevent variables Y: missing patterns (each day from 2019-01-01 to 2020-12-31)
  • Vertically, variable ‘max_steady_wind’ has the most missing values as it ranks number-one at the bottom column-sort.
  • Horizontally, for missing values patterns, pattern ‘max_steady_wind’ took place most frequently up to 71 times, which means there are 71 rows of data with ‘max_steady_wind’ value missing as NA. The next pattern is ‘min_temp, max_temp, max_steady_wind, total_daily_precipitation, description’ with frequency 5 times, which means 5 rows of data miss values for all variables. The complete pattern-rank goes from top to bottom as the right row-sort shows.
library(data.table)
library(ggplot2)
library(grid)
library(extracat)

load('dat.dt.RData')

vars.considered<-c('min_temp','max_temp','max_steady_wind','total_daily_precipitation','description')
what<-dat[,..vars.considered]
visna(what,sort='b',return.data=T,opts=list(mar=c(0.5,0.2)))

2.Deciding-Factor Analysis

bike[,all(registered+casual==total)]
## [1] TRUE

The overall trend graph shows that:

  • In 2019, most bike-sharing activities took place between March to October, in other words, between Spring to early Fall, among which Spring is the peak season users tend to engage in the bike-sharing, with daily average rental amount approching to 15,000.
  • Under the impact of the pandemic, 2020 witnesssed a sharp decline of total rental amount and the trend tends to be more oscillating. Since May, the amount of registered users decreased while casual users increased.

Variable-Dependency

We want to explore how total rental amount of bike-sharing relates to each variable. Since variables are not the same type, we would split them into quantitative varibles and qualitative varibles and analyze seperately.

Heatmap on the left shows such three main clusters/groups of bike-sharing rental amount as High rental amount, Low rental amount and Medium rental amount (from bottom to top). Accordingly, the right four scatterplots present how these three rental groups relate to each quantitative variables. Note that the transparency of data points represents the magnitude of total rental amount: the more total rental amount each point holds, the darker it will be. Based on the plots, it is clearly observed that:

  • More bike-sharing activities took place when temperature was above 20 degrees Celsius (68 degrees Fahrenheit) and less people cycled when it was cold, especially when temperature was subzero.
  • People prefer to rent and ride bicycles on non-rainy days with precipitation below 10mm. Noticeable, some users did enjoy rainy-cycling with precipitation above 20mm and few users even choose the service when it rained over 70mm.
  • Non-windy days with 15-30 km/h wind usually attracted more users to the bike-sharing service. Indeed, some users would choose the service when it blew at over 50 km/h.

2.2 qualitative-Varible Analysis

  • Weekday (weekday of the date)
  • Season
  • Description (weather type of the date)
library(ggridges)

bike1<-melt(bike1,
      id.vars=c('date','season','weekday'),
      variable.name='what',
      value.name='number')

weather[bike1,on=.(date)]->dat1
na.omit(dat1)->dat1

dat1[,year:=year(date)]
dat1[,month:=month(date)]
dat1[,day:=mday(date)]
dat1[,wday:=wday(date)]
# Weekday
dat1[,weekday:=ordered(weekday,unique(dat1[,.(wday,weekday)])[order(-wday),weekday])]
pweekday <- ggplot(dat1, aes(x = number, y = weekday, fill=weekday))+
  geom_density_ridges(show.legend=F)+
  facet_grid(rows=vars(what))+
  theme_bw()

# Season
dat1[,season:=ordered(season,c('Spring','Summer','Fall','Winter'))]
pseason <- ggplot(dat1, aes(x = number, y = season, fill=season))+
  geom_density_ridges(show.legend=F)+
  facet_grid(rows=vars(what))+
  theme_bw()

# Description
pdesp <- ggplot(dat1, aes(x = number, y = description,fill=description))+
  geom_density_ridges(show.legend=F)+
  facet_grid(rows=vars(what))+
  theme_bw()

pweekday

pseason

pdesp

Based on the ridge-plots, we could observe that:

  • Saturday and Sunday tend to attract more users to cycle, whose distributions center on higher total rental amount (over 10,000). Noticeably, Monday through Friday almost have the same distributions, which may imply users’ daily commuting necessity.
  • Spring and Summer are users’ favorite seasons to engage in the bike-sharing activiteis while Fall attracted certain amount of users as well. Besides, there was a great variation in Spring’s total rental amount, which implies the distinctive year-on-year decline in 2020, i.e. the Covid-pandemic year.
  • As expected, sunny days (Weather events not reported) are users’ top choices to ride bicycles while people cycled less on rainy and snowy days (Rain, Fograin, Snowfall, Snowfallrain). Surprisingly, thunderstrom days (ThunderstormRain and FogThunderstromRain) did not undermine people’s passion for bike-sharing and this phenomenon could be attributed to residents’ adaptation to frequent thunderstroms.
